Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the noodles. When boiling, add the @Egg Noodle Nest{2} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, trim the @Pak Choi{1}(trimmed), then thinly slice widthways. Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Cut the @Lime{1} into wedges.

Trim and peel the @Carrot{1}(trimmed and peeled). Use the #peeler{} to peel long ribbons down the length of the carrot, stopping at the core.

Drain the @King Prawns{150%grams}. 

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the garlic and stir-fry until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir the @Bulgogi Sauce{150%grams} and @Water for the Sauce{50%ml} into the garlic, then bring to the boil.

Stir in the prawns and cook for another ~{3-4%minutes}.

Next, add the carrot ribbons and pak choi to the pan. Simmer until the prawns are cooked through and the veg is tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the prawns are cooked, add the noodles and a squeeze of lime juice to the sauce. Toss to coat the noodles in the sauce, stirring frequently until everything is piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Taste and add more @salt{}, @pepper{} or lime juice if needed. Add a splash of @water{if needed} if you feel it needs it.

Share the bulgogi prawn noodles between your #bowls{}. Serve any remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over. Enjoy!